data.message:
Coriandra lead the way by a considerable distance. She needed to generate considerably heat in order to fly, and her glow would serve both purposes of warning away 

potential sky-bullies and ensuring her teammates did not lose sight of her. Zedekial was riding with Carrefour, and Justin was hanging back with Gitchael, who had 

never seen any reason to learn to fly properly. Justin could help stabilize him somewhat, but he still tended to lose control and crash quite often. Apparently his 

apprentices were not the only ones in need of 'on-the-job-training' and she percieved this as the most brilliant team of dumbasses the Tribunal could have possibly 

assembled. For all their potential power and simple genius, they were horrible klutzes, each one flawed in an exceptional way, herself included. She had been a mere 

sister of the order when she'd been called to serve Gitch. A more knowledgeable and pious sister would have never been able to adjust to this chaotic learning 

environment, and she knew her flaws were what had made Gitch insist that no other sister besides herself accompanied them on their mission. The other sisters would 

have stood down to her authority on all things if Gitchell instructed them to, but she would sense their disapproval and hear their thoughts, which would taint her own 

decisions about what was best for her..........team? friends? students? She wasn't even quite sure who she was to these people, or who they might be to her, in their 

entirety. If three Heritors weren't enough, she felt sure the Tribunal would offer it to Carrefour. She was sure he had the qualifications, since lack of magickal 

education had never been a discreditor for a Heritor. It wasn't about the zapping and popping and fixing everything with a wave of your hand, those were just things 

most elder Heritors had learned. The qualifications for Heritor were Courage, tenacity, creative problem solving, and a deep seated instinct of what was right or 

wrong. Carrefour had continued traveling with them long past what duty to a heritor could possibly require, and he'd nearly lost his life in horrifying and unpleasant 

ways. Nobody would have blamed him for retreating, and yet he stayed, he fought, he won. He might not be ready for the Tribunal's bargain yet, but if they offered, she 

was sure he'd accept, which was why she found herself treating him like a Heritor already. She wondered, idly if Gitchael had noticed that or if he just assumed she 

was merely complying with his wishes to treat everyone as equals on this team. It would be slightly different if she were treating Carrefour as an equal instead of 

seeing him as one. She would probably have been hesitant to trust him with Zedekiel's passage, since the new heritor knew even less about magic than Carrefour did. 

With the added protection of Deke's wishing star, she saw little reason to worry about either of them at all. There would be nothing the two of them couldn't get out 

of--She was far more worried about what physical damages Gitchael might be inflicting upon himself plowing into the ground like that. Every time she saw him take a 

nosedive, she winced a little, grateful that he was just a speck on the horizon from this distance and she didn't have a better view of him repeatedly going 'splat.'

The Djinn had a much better view of Deke and Carr, when Deke blurted out to the centaur, "Maybe I should start learning that too. From the looks of how Gitch is faring 

Aquatic cambions need all the practice they can get!"

"Your aquatic forms do make it harder to navigate through the air, Deke. Air currents and water currents are not anywhere near as similar as your high school science 

teachers once led you to believe." He glanced back with an impish look in his eye, "Wanna play anyway?"

"Fuck yeah! How do I start?" He listened as Carr explained that levitation was an instinct. It kicked in when you felt a fear of falling, but wasn't easy to control 

without wings to stabilize yourself with. Humanoid forms were not at all aerodynamic, and tended to twist and spin. All of his psychokinetic energy would be expended 

just keeping himself off the ground, and he would have to figure out how to balance on his own. "Sounds like riding a bike, and you get to hang on to the seat." He 

hoped he was more coordinated than Gtich was, but for all he knew Gitch's human half could have been a ninja and it was just that difficult.

"Slide off my back and grab hold of my tail, don't worry, I have excellent bowel control." The Sea Warlock did as he was instructed and was soon soaring, Arms and 

tentacles spreading to clutch at the whipping winds. "The difference in tails might make this easier for you than Gitch has it--his fin is designed to cut through 

currents, yours can kind of catch them!"

There was a little bit of webbing between this tentacles, and he experimented in spreading them out in various patterns until settling on one that seemed to feel 

right. He heard Coriandra stifle a cry up ahead as he let go of the Zibataur's tail to grab his two front tentacles and spread them out like wings or a cape. He hoped 

he hadn't scared Cory too much, in the process, because it seemed to be working! He kept his balance, and his string of loud cusswords rang triumphantly through the 

sky in a cheerful rage that utterly confused the Native Lilin. She floated back towards them in a state of utter confusion that made Deke feel a little guilty.

"He's fine Cory!" Carrefour cheered at her, since Deke was still in the throes of two fuckinayes and a couple rockons, his emotional state wasn't conducive to actualy 

communication. "I won't let him fall, don't worry!"

"You should really warn me before you train him like that. If I had a physical heart it would have stopped right then. Do you not think I trust you?" Cory hollered 

back, she was feeling positively maternal at the moment, especially as a rogue wind current pulled Deke away from Carrefour. "Let him go a bit! If he loses control 

completely you can catch him, but don't baby him every time a stiff breeze catches his tail!"

She really did have faith in him, Carrefour thought as he called out instructions and helpful hints and Deke figured out how to bank and turn between currents. He 

might always be a little slow, but he was doing admirable well for a guy who was half squid and flying. "I'm impressed, Deke! Gitch has been working on flying for 

centuries, and you figured it out in a matter of minutes!"

Deke grabbed onto to the centaur again, huffing and puffing, "I haven't exactly mastered it yet, but it sure is fun trying to figure it out! Sorry if I sacred you 

Coriandra, I should have given you a heads up, but I figured even if you didn't try to stop me, I wouldn't be afraid of falling if I knew you'd catch me. I had to 

ditch the training wheels." They had paused to hover while the talked and Gitch and Justin were finally catching up.

"Maybe I should have had Deke as an instructor." Gitch grinned, showing no envy or malice, though he felt both of them at once.

"Not too late, though, is it Gitch?" Deke challenged. "You can shoot us up a lot farther than I could get on my own, I'd be okay to float back down on my own, but I 

ain't good enough to be able to catch you, so as long as everybody else stayed on the ground, you be kicking off your training wheels."

Gitch let go of Justin's shoulder and grabbed on to Zedekiel. He gave Coriandra his most obstinate look and commanded, "Everybody wait for us on the ground. We have 

Guy Stuff to attend to." Then he rocketed up into the sky with Deke and let go when they were too high up for anyone to catch them.

Deke spread himself out and caught the currents, which were much stronger up here and easier to hold on to. He banked from one to another, trying to get back towards 

the spinning figure of Gitchell, who was still plummeting at the moment. He didn't think he'd be able to catch him, but he certainly had never tried before, so he 

really didn't know. Besides, it was fun! Rolling, tumbling, diving, expanding--the adrenaline pumping through his brain wasn't half bad either! he was almost 

disappointed when Gitch finally flung out his arms and managed to embrace the air, stabilizing himself. His hands were clenched open, and Deke could just vaguely make 

out some sort of energy feild that spread out around his arms, like an outline, or an aura. It was almost perfectly invisible, but the air that went around it was 

something the eye couls actually detect. "You got it?" he hollered as he glided into Gitch's range.

Gitch looked more surprised than anything, "Yeah! I'm good!" They wouldn't be able to talk much until they got down to a less volatile turbulance, but what few words 

they could shout at each other were purely triumphant. It took them nearly three hours to glide down to a point where the others could intercept them, and if they 

wouldn't have succeeded, Gitch would have made the trip in seconds--pulling his body back together would have required hours. Deke was exhausted and bellyflopped 

gratefully onto the centaur's back, cokeyed and sideways, the way a horse would carry someone who was either unconscious or dead. Deke insisted he was the latter. 

Gitch however had far more energy, and continued parcticing manuvers with Justin long after Cory and Carr had picked a floating island to camp on for the night.

"This is the Aisle of Sequesters," Carrefour told them. My people were given charge of the islands in the sky shortly after the first winged centaur was born--I think 

his name was Perry Stapleton, but that was ten years before I got here. Before that the dragons took care of them, but the Tribunal decided the Zibataurs would make 

more efficent caretakers, and the dragons already have enough to keep them occupied. The poor guys are constantly helping flightless people out with errand and 

travel--some construction, even! We're about three orbits away from The Aisle of Brothers, but I should be able to get us a visit with Ashtarot. He's never minded 

talking to me before."

"Ashtarot is still alive? I thought he only lived there in memory." Coriandra blustered in amazement.

"Most people think that Astaroth and Ashtarot are one in the same, and that he perished on earth during the Revolutionary war, but that's only partly true. Ashtarot 

was what he was using as a human name at the time, and he wasn't fully incarnated. The man he chose to run the country and helped to win the war, turned on him. George 

clapped his muse in iron shackles, which seperated Ashtarot from the rest of his consciousness and removed the avatar's powers. It died, and Astaroth felt the pain. He 

also had lost his human half, his cambion powers. He's often told me how much he wishes he could go back, especially with how few Cambion Heritors we have left. I'm 

sure he will be pleased that we have found a couple extras."

"Indeed I am!" the voice rang out from above their heads and they looked up at a creature that was weird even by Zamargodian standards, "But you should take it a bit 

easier on them, this one seems to be very unconscious." The centaur above them had wings of flame, and his left hand had been replaced by a silver Crayfish claw, which 

he now used to gesture towards Zedekiel, who was very soundly sleeping indeed. Astaroth had greeted them in a voice louder than a cyclone's howl, and Gitch and Justin 

hurried over from where they had been working out. "Care to introduce me to your friends, Carrefour? My telepathy died with my human half."

"Aster, this is Gitchell Cambion, Prince Heritor, and his First Apprentice Justin Cambion." Carrefour was used to Astaroth's voice and was surprised to see Coriandra 

looking almost afraid of the old angel. "Our Tutor, of course, Sister Coriandra of Nemath, and the Second Apprentice, who really needed a nap, is Zedekiel."

"A Cambion as well?" Astaroth asked in a voice that was as hushed as Carrefour had ever heard from him. It still sounded like a distant avalanche.

"Yes, C'thulhu named him very recently. I assure you I did not push his endurance in training. He did that himself, and now he really is exhausted." Carrefour chatted 

so casually with the old god that even Gitchell stared in disbelief.

"Then do you mind if I stay until he wakes? I have heard such impressive things about all of you, I would really like to get acquainted." He gestured with the lobster 

claw in Gitch's general direction, and a large book manifested itself in the dust. "I believe this is what you initially came for, the second Gateway spell. I wrote it 

myself, so if you have any questions, do not hesitiate to ask."

"Why didn't you just wait at your castle?" Gitch asked, in perfect accordance with Astaroth's instructions.

"Everybody in seven universes knows of your quest. I felt it was only proper, should anyone try to interfere with you, to screw with their heads as much as I see fit. 

Anyone trying to track you will assume you went to my castle. You will not. The people there will never know you have the second ritual, nor that you have met with me. 

When my human half died I lost my telepathic abilities, so only a very old and skilled individual could ever read my mind. If a device cannot recieve it cannot send. 

You can read me Gitch, as can a handful of others, none of whom could be coerced into betraying the Tribunal."

"Thank you Aster,"Gitch responded, naturally having read the beings mind and finding that he preferred to be called by nicknames. He seemed to value what little 

anonymity he could get, and was ultimately trustworthy. He'd mastered the art of keeping a secret without telling any lies. "Should we be concerned about 

interference?"

"Were you not? You do not seem so stupid."

"Of course we have been concerned, and we have run into minor interference," He paused irritated as Cory goraned and rolled her eyes at his use of the word 'minor', 

"I'm asking if you have information that would validate those concerns." At this point Deke moaned too, it appeared his nap would soon be over. It had only lasted six 

hours.

"I only have rumors and suppositions, I'm afraid. You know there are many in our world who would wish to see the First World destroyed or an end to the human race, but 

these are people with little power, so they cannot be readily tracked. All anyone knows is that a lot of human haters have gone missing recently and even the Tribunal 

cannot locate them." Astaroth finished disappointedly.

"Nobody can fly under the radar forever, my fiberoptic and cool looking friend," Deke half mumbled still rubbing his eyes. "Individually their powers might be beneath 

notice, but they will have to put their powers together in order to get anything treachorous done. That will register. Especially if they violate any universal laws, 

and I am fairly certain they can't do too much damage to us without the universe becoming very aggravated."

"Zedekiel, I see the Lilin Sisters weren't exaggerating when they spoke of you intelligence. Permit me to intorduce mysel....."

"Astaroth, I presume?" Deke almost chuckled at the look of surprise on the old god's young face. "Gitch has an old picture of you in his Grimoire. I found it when I 

was looking up herbal attributes when we were packing for this journey, and I am sure the Sisters exaggerated quite a bit, I just have common sense. Those lovely 

ladies are way too kind."

"If common sense wasn't a form of genius, Cambion Heritors would not be so rare." Astaroth informed him. "Any other qualifiactaion can be overlooked by the Tribunal 

when naming a Cambion Heritor, but they must have common sense." He looked at Carrefour and again grew serious, "I hope you plan on staying with this mission, Carr. 

Farbeit from me to guess what the Tribunal is thinking, but just from knowing you I must assume you'd make an excellent back-up plan. If you find yourselves in need of 

another instant Heritor..."

"Well, that's obvious to all of us," Coriandra blurted out, "But thank you for mentioning it anyway. I don't think we've given him as much verbal affirmation as he 

deserves, but I assure you, Brother, I think of him as no less a Heritor as any of the others. They all have VERY individual needs and when the time is right for him, 

Carrefour will meet one of the brothers of the Tribunal. It's not like any of the others are in danger of dying, so it's unlikely he an alternate being held in 

reserve."

"When did they start making Lilin Sisters with common sense?" Astaroth inquired.

"I had to learn on my own. If I had been made with it, I would be the only one on this trip without a challenge, and that just wouldn't be fair." Coriandra found 

herself staring defiantly into the eyes of one of the oldest and most powerful demigods Zamargados had ever known. Only the Grand High Lilitu had power to equal his, 

and the Tribunal would not interfere in anything Astaroth chose to do. "I'm not your ordinary girl anymore, Grand Father. I cannot afford that luxury." Astaroth hugged 

her, and even one as old and powerful as he was came away with a mild sunburn from that contact. Still he didn't pull away. He held her for a good long moment.

"That's from your companions too." He whispered in her ear. Then Zedekiel started asking questions again and they kept talking until after the first sun's rise, when 

it was agreed by all to part company before someone saw them together. Gitch and Deke both seemed to think they had discovered something of great importance in the 

ritual of the Second Gate. It involved Solomon's Triangle of manifestation, although Astaroth insisted that Solomon had learned it from HIM. Gitch already had the 

third Gateway spell, which involved the sigils of the necronomicon and had done some experimenting with crossing the two schools of Magick. He and Marty seemed to 

believe they had found a way to work what they had into a base upon which to build their new 'gate-thingy.' Since they weren't sure if it was going to be a gateway, a 

handcart to hell, or something even weirder they had not even imagined yet, they had started referring to it as the 'gate-thingy' as the most accurate technical term 

they could come up with.

Gitch and Coriandra were communing with the puckwudies, who were buzzing back and forth between the questers and the other gateways. The puckwudgies were trying to 

verify the heaps of information that Gitchell had given to himself from the other side. Gich had managed to freeze the soft spot that let them communicate with Earth, 

but it wasn't entirely mobile. Now it hung in the air like a black hole, approximately the size of an average vanity mirror, the last soft spot left over from the gate 

at haunchieville. Physically, they were not in the same spot as their team was on the other side. Zamargados and Earth occupied the same physical space, at the same 

approximated time when gateways could appear, but Kane and Tara were in Ashland Wisconsin and this particular location was closer to Milwaukee. There was no logical 

explanation for why the rift was cockeyed, but this side could not be moved. Deke, Carrefour and Justin were pouring over the rituals the puckwudgies had managed to 

verify already, and Gitch had blacked out the portions that had proven to be false. They had assembled the vessel they intended to use, but unless they managed to 

blast through the veil on the other side, they'd die trying to go through. They'd nicknamed the structure 'The phantom shitter' because the outer hull was disguised as 

an old outhouse, which would blend in almost anywhere they landed in Northern Wisconsin. Inside the shell they'd constructed a bubble dimension, outfitted with a small 

studio apartment. The console looked like a bunch of old computers hotwired together, with a 32 inch monitor that was made before 1999. It had two towers and the main 

chunk of an old TI994A, a laser mouse and generic keyboard. The jimmyrigged monstrosity froze up and glitched out constantly, loaded down with programs that shouldn't 

work at all in that configuration, but it tapped into an important chunk of earthling magic--the mysterious internet connections that joined every phone in everybody's 

pockets, every computer, including crappy laptops that sought out free WiFi, and every stupid facebook page and twitter post that detailed every passing thought 

anybody had to offer. He had set it up, not to process anything technical, but to connect to every human at whatever point in history they had ever touched a computer, 

wether it was a TRS80 in 1980-something for keyboarding class, or a Pentium processed piece of plastic that just played 3D games. Everybody in their collective 

subconscious believed in the wonders of computers on some level, and it was a belief the never dared to question. No matter how educated one was in Computer Tech, 

nobody really understood how the damned things worked. Sometimes you could fix them, but sometimes you couldn't and the reasons why were gibberish and hokum. Most 

folks accepted that the machines were smarter than they were. What they couldn't accept was that the machines weren't even real. They were pretty plastic packaging 

that accentuated a psychic connection between humans that had always been there, helping psychics find lost children and warning elders when it was going to storm. 

Their tablets and I-phones were connected to their brainwaves, cybernetic psychics with safety filters in place so nobody could screw anything up. With the cybernetic 

connections in place, they didn't need Djinns to meditate to widen the connecting cord, but they had busted the star and summoned some anyway in the hopes that their 

meditiations would weaken the veil even further. The Grand Mother Djinn herself had gone to the Astarot to beseech their aid as well, and now both the brothers and the 

sisters throughout the land were working away at that one tiny spot, focusing on Joe Kane. If they would have focused on the human girl, she might have been damaged 

should they break through, and Kane was easier to zone in on.

The sky above was frozen. No suns moving, no clouds sailing by, indicating that their humanoid agents on the other side were all asleep. The energy readings from 

Gitchell's human half indicated that it was nearly out of regenerative magic. It was dying, or dead already, since it had never truly been alive in the first place. It 

was being empowered by a shadow of what Gitch really was, and only had three times the energy of a normal human, Without the gateway there was no way for it to 

recharge, and once the gateway was open and Gitch's geis expired, Joseph Charles Kane would cease to exist. Some humans would remember him, but nobody would wonder 

where he had gone. He'd simply fade away. The subconscious minds of his loved ones, his human family, would generate a few fake e-mails and phone calls to present the 

illusion that he was still out there somewhere. A cambion's earthling demise never caused any human to suffer; they'd believe he was fine until the last one who 

remembered passed away. Nobody would miss him. However, he still wanted his cat. The tiny little lady had absorbed enough of his cambion energy to be allowed to come 

home with him. For eighteen years she had been his sole confidant, the only one he could talk to, the only one who truly knew him for who and what he was and loved him 

all the same. Humans might not be worth saving, but their pets certainly qualified. He was determined to get her back.

Carrefour knew deep down inside that the universes were unlikely to yield a doorway based on the power of love for a human teenager and a cat, and toiled away 

tirelessly inside the phantom shitter, inscribing all the sigils, veve's and symbols from the old gateways into the walls of the ship. He carved them in and filled the 

carvings with the purest molten silver, connecting them all to each other and wiring them into the cobbled computer that would guide and empower the vessel. He, Justin 

and Gitchell would ride inside, there was barely enough room for the three of them, but Gitch had to try getting into that world corporeally, and Carrefour would have 

to stay in the vessel to maintain the atmospheric bubble. Justin would need his powers and his human body wasn't conditioned to access them. Deke would go through 

first, astrally, targeting his daughter's love and guiding the vessel behind him, and Cory would accompany him, since she was made of energy, she could dance in the 

outer reaches of any universe without risk, and she could guide and protect Deke, possibly even use her energies to help pop the earth bubble and get him through. The 

sigils on the wall pulsated and glowed under the centaurs probing fingertips, he cast a seperate golem spell on each one as he finished it, this ship wouldn't just be 

alive, it would qualify as enough artificial life forms to qualify as a species, and all of them linked together in one common life-mission--bringing everyone 

together.

"Coiandra, I don't want you to do this," Gitch took advantage of a break in in the tireless stream of puckwudgies, "I know that you'l be willing to expend all of your 

energy trying to break through to Earth. You'd cease to exist and it might not even be enough."

"The astral chord you're using to get across doesn't allow you to go in reverse. If we don't break through we're all dead. How will my survival benefit anyone?" 

Coriandra spoke pure logic, "I'm not any more powerful than any of my sisters, and we've got all the information recorded. There might not even be another chance if we 

fail, so I might as well die trying or succeed. Any other option would be historically recorded as genocidal cowardice, and if this plane of existence survives, it 

would then become just like Earth. At the very least my example should be a good one."

"If you die breaking through to earth, you'll be transformed into a tectite marble, You would never be reborn."

"A risk we are all taking. All we have to go on here are a handful of theoretical paradoxes that do not turn out well, but they are all just theories. Tezcatlipoca and 

C'thulhu are counting on us, and Maximon lives in their veil. We must assume he's on our side too."

"Maximon is too human to count on. He's a masochistic demigod who never helped me out in all my years as Heritor. The Tribunal is a majority rule, they are almost 

never unanimous in any decision, and one this complex would be folly not to question. We cannot count on Max!" Gitch was using the most persuasive vocal inflections he 

could muster.

"Gitchael, you arguments make no sense. I am sworn to serve you and your apprentices. If we don't puncture the veil you will all be dead and the only way I will be 

able to serve you is with tartar sauce. This is an intense situation, but do not let your feelings for me or any of us cloud your judgement. We all need to be at the 

top of our game." She was concerned Gitch was cracking under the pressure. All the other members of the team were cambions. She knew from their mind what fear they had 

of death. She was incapable of fear, and Gitch seemed to be projecting his own fears onto her. "I'm not some weak, effeminate thing, Gitchell. You do not need to 

protect me."

"I just want to be sure this is what you truly want. None of the others are obligated, but you are bound by an oath."

"I knew what it could entail, and no, I would not choose to break it just because of a worst-case scenario. When I swore that oath, I had no idea how worthy you might 

be. You and your mission are worth dying for. If they weren't it would be just you and I standing here. My decision is made." She smiled at him, a peaceful, unworried 

smile that was amazingly reassuring. The puckwudgies had petered out, and what few details they had yet to confirm or disregard were just going to go in a gray area. 

Gitch joined up with Deke to find out what was going on on the other side of the twisted mirror, and Coriandra shimmered out, to travel at lightspeed to her sisters 

and the brotherhood of Ashtarot, to check on their progress. Nobody even noticed when a very young and tiny puckwudgie flew past Gitch and Deke and right into the Dark 

side of the mirror, but Old Joe Kane almost dropped the lighter one when the little bug boy flew out into his face.

"Holy Crapmotheroffutctards!" Kane exploded as the glowing blue brat veered to the left at the last minute, brushing across the humanoid's cheek. "How did you get 

through there?" He demanded whirling around, as Tara grabbed the mirror from his distracted hand.

"A tinkerbell just came out of the mirror!" She reported excitedly to her father. "Somebody just came through! It can be done!"

"There's no such thing as tinkerbell," Deke muttered confused. "You sure it wasn't a puckwudgie? was it blue?"

"Of course she meant a puckwudgie," Gitch exploded with surprise. "What else could she have seen? Haunchies are too big to fit through her little hand mirror and 

puckwudgies have their own personal timeline--a small one COULD slip through."

The little blue fellow flew politely up to the mirror, he looked like he was about five-hundred and forty, equivalent to a nine or ten year old human. Kane had to 

translate for him since they couldn't read his empathic waves through the dimensional window. "He says he had a theory, more of a gut instinct. You know how these 

little buggers think, he just went with it. He has no idea what significance his action might have had, he just felt it was important."

"It was, you mundane dolt!" Gitchell playfully insulted his worser half, "Care to tell the rest of the class what it was?"

"Provided his magical nature doesn't erase him too quickly, he's an asset to our combined power on this side." Kane was developing a meta-migraine in the lowermost 

section of his human brain, it happened whenever he connected to his lower consciousness, the second neural cluster at the base of his spine. In spite of his 

biokinetic modifications, full human forms were not designed to function as cambion hosts. "I suppose, that if we can ALL get to the soft spot on this side, Me, the 

cat the girl.....Our Cat is not going to like us wading out with her into the lake...."

"Our little blue friend can phase back through the mirror, a tiny ray of light to guide us to the weakest point." Gitch saw the little blue boy sitting quietly on 

Kane's shoulder, cross legged and glowing like a christmas light. "He seems to be fine as far as his energy levels are concerned, he might be drawing off of your past 

or future energies, since he can't connect to your timeline directly. If you keep him close he should be fine."

"He should also be extremely noticeable. How are we supposed to go snooping around a highly visible and very restricted section of the lake, with a bright blue tiny 

person buzzing around our heads? He is way too big to pass off as a firefly and the wrong color. I had planned to go under the cover of darkness, but with him along, 

that will only make us more noticeable. I can only project enough of an illusion to mask myself, and even then it's not the same as being invisible. You know my limits 

here, you slimy, flippered freak!" This was brining new meaning to the term 'self-loathing'. Gitch totally did not comprehend the seriousness of his situation.

"He's small enough to fit in a decent sized flashlight, you just have to take out the battery assembly and the bulb." Deke suggested.

"But he doesn't turn off, and there's no telling what the pesticides outside might do to him." Kane reminded them, "He has to be free to ensure his safety, I don't 

even know what they might be spraying our local flora with, it's not like they're going to post the honest truth anywhere I could access it."

"What about my backpack-purse?" Tara interjected, "It's big enough to hold him and some herbs or whatever to help keep his environment friendly, the fabric will filter 

out a lot of crap from the air, and it'll mute his light a decent amount. I can leave it half unzipped in case he has to get away because of environmental toxins."

"Considering how close Excel Energy is to the Gateway zone, we'll have to come up with something better. That power plant pumps out tons of gases that are toxic to US! 

Your father must have some sort of air filter or something in here or the little bugger would be dead already."

"All I've got in there is a can of glade in the bathroom and a febreeze air freshener by the sink." Deke volunteered, anything else was way beyond his budget.

"Baking Soda!" Kane blurted out, "That's one of the main ingredients in febreeze! If we make him a nice thick bed of baking soda in the bottom of your purse, it might 

absorb enough of the toxins--especially since he exist outside of the timestream, he can keep going back to when the air was freshest!"

"There's a box in the fridge and one in the cupboard." Deke offered, "Fair warning, the one in the fridge is in there for a reason."

Tara decided to take a test run. She had found a Ramen Noodle box that fit in the bottom of her bag, filled it with Baking Soda, and covered it with a bandanna, held 

down with hairpins that had been pushed through the cardboard. She added a few hair scrunchies to act as furniture for the tiny little guy, and tightened up the straps 

so he wouldn't be bounced around too much, if she had to carry him on her back. Right now she was headed for the hiking trail that wrapped around the city, it had once 

been railroad tracks, at least two sets, but the city had ripped those up and paved the trail they left behind. She was headed for the southermost trail, which was 

furthest away from the lakeshore and the stinking power plant. She cradled the bag, supporting the bottom, trying to keep his little habitat as stable as possible. He 

was hovering in the center, and she kept peeking in at him. If anyone saw her, they would probably assume she had a kitten or puppy in the bag, she just had to hope 

nobody approached her wanting to see. The puckwudgie was amazing! A perfectly formed little boy wearing a tiny pair of trunks that would have fit too tight on any toy 

action figure, yet they looked like normal shorts. The tiny little seams were nowhere near as out of scale as doll clothes tended to be. Pity she wasn't much of a 

Barbie girl anymore, he might enjoy some of those little plastic combs and brushes, even if they were a little big for him. If he had a name, he had no way of 

communicating it to them, but she was beginning to pick up on the 'vibes' he used to communicate with humans. "I need something to call you besides just 'puckwudgie.' 

You should have a name." He seemed to like the idea. She felt his little heart go pitter-pat and he glowed a little brighter. "How about Mickey? My father's human name 

was Marty, and Mickey's kind of close. It's also short for Micheal, like the angel, and you look like an angel to me." The little guy lit up again and she felt the 

little tingle that made her think he was happy. It was kind of like someone his size was tickling her from the inside. They were crossing the old railroad bridge, near 

the skateboard park, right past the baseball field and playground. It was odd how the city had arranged this mess, there was this big huge cluster of kids crap and 

then the trail just went on forever, without much of anything to see after you crossed the bridge. It cut behind an old folks home, one of many in this town. So many 

in fact that nobody really bothered to learn the names unless they lived there. Storage space for the unwanted elderly and useless retarded. Nobody cared about those 

poor forgotten souls but their dealers. The economy of this area was heavily dependent on half formed fuctards selling their free prescription pills. If the air 

pollution didn't kill the tiny little empath, the emptiness of the resident humans might. Off to the other side was another complex, which she imagined was a 

dormitory, though she really had no clue. It had once been a hospital and before that a mansion, back when somebody up here had a little money, a couple hundred years 

ago. The buildings still stood, with turrets and conical tower roofs, like castles that had been converted into efficiency apartments. Tombstones marking the death of 

our ancestors dreams. They were beautiful, yet creepy, like a Disney villain's lair that somehow lost it's magic. Mickey darted out of his little canvas house to grab 

a ladyslipper for her, and tucked it into her raven hair. "Mickey, you know that's dangerous. What if somebody would have stepped on you?" he shyly peeked out at her 

and shook his little head smiling. "I know you're fast, but they're really clumsy. You have to be careful, little man!" she stepped up her pace a little, there were 

some ruins up ahead, and unless some teenagers were trying to get lucky, they could stop there for a while and see how well he was doing. She had her cell with her, 

and Zane had gotten ahold of an ATV from his human brother, for a quick pickup if anything should go wrong. The ruins were about six blocks away from Excel Energy, so 

they'd be able to get a good idea of how their little smurfling handled those pollutant levels. He seemed to be fine. He could even flit around outside his little tent 

inspecting the local plant life for up to five minutes before returning to his room to rest. Tara set him down and texted Joe and Jim Kane to let them know their 

little blue buddy was all right and where they were. She wasn't entirely sure Joe's baby brother was entirely human. Jim was actually shorter and skinnier than Joe 

was, with buck teeth and ears that stuck out. He actually looked more elfin than his older brother, but far less creepy. He had dishwater blond hair like Justin, in a 

neat buzzcut that he'd probably done himself, and his eyes were the color of windex. Everybody on both sides of the mirror had told her that cambions don't come with 

blue eyes, but from everything else they had said, a lot of those old rules were turning up broken, and Jim made her think of leprechauns and imps. He was always 

smiling, his eyes always full of mischief. He was very hyperkinetic, and kept blurting out nonsensical and crazy plans that made little sense but sure sounded like 

fun! Joseph Kane seemed happier with his brother around as well, and for a pureblood human, Jim Kane seemed incredibly at ease with a tiny blue kid flying around on 

butterfly wings. The puckwudgie surprised him, but he had instantly accepted it, inisisting that he'd seen weirder things whenever his big brother was around. Jim was 

coming out to meet her and check on Mickey. They'd both thought it was cool that she'd given him a name. The darker brother would stay where he was, wading through the 

contaminated sediment area with the mirror, trying to pick up a sense of where the weak spot might be. Mickey zipped away towards the sound of the Three-wheeler as it 

approached. The little thing was fearless, having come from a land where dragons prowled the skies and nothing could ever catch him. He rode back perched on the 

headlight, and Jim was laughing uncontrollably. Tara rushed towards them terrified of what the exhuast fumes might be doing to her little friend.

"He never saw it coming? Gawd, I wish I'd have been there! Nothing ever surprises him on this side anymore. I wish I could have seen his face when you popped out of 

that mirror!"

"You can understand him? Like, word for word?" Tara was having a real hard time believing this guy was purebred human.

"He doesn't talk in words, it's more like a daydream. You have to let your own mind filter it out to turn it into words, pictures, sights sounds--whatever your mind 

can recreate in your mind." Jim explained, "Just let you mind go blank, and then let him in. It's easy for me; I've done a lot of mushrooms."

"Are you really just a normal human being?" Tara didn't expect him to change his earlier answer, "I mean I thought I was but then I find out that my Father passed on 

some sort of magic DNA, isn't it possible that you could be like him?"

"Nobody in our family has ever been accused of being normal, but Joey is the only one who can do all that magicky shit." Jim assured her, "My mom has a little bit of 

precognition, but not enough to really matter. We're all extra tough--durable--but Joey's the only one who qualifies as superhuman. The rest of us break bones, get 

sick, heal at a normal rate, blah,blah,blah...."

"But I thought I was normal. How can you be absolutely SURE you're not something more?" She was really trying to understand his certainty.

"Because I have a wife and a three year old daughter back on the rez. My daughter is a cambion, Bethany, my wife and I just have recessive genes. I will do anything I 

have to here, because my little girl is going to go to my brother's other world some day. I knew that as soon as she was born. My brother knew it ten months before 

that. In three years, He's going to take her across to Zamargados, he dreamed it already. Not all of his dreams are prophetic, and even the ones that are never turn 

out exactly like the dreams. He's been blowing this one off for almost four years, and he isn't going to start having faith in it now, but I know my little girl is 

gonna make it over there. We're gonna fix this." Their little blue buddy was started to get a little dark, so she popped him into his habitat to recharge. He could 

survive without it for almost an hour, but the little shit never knew when to come back inside. "You better be a damn good babysitter, Tara. He's just a little boy."

"Gitch says his mother almost had a heart attack when she found out he was over here. She tried to get through the mirror herself, but the gap is too small." She 

really felt bad for the tiny blue woman. "At least we can be pretty certain he'll make it back home safe. He'll be drawn back through the same way he was drawn into 

our world, and magick will protect him there."

"Provided he doesn't get run over by whatever metaphysical hippy bus they plan to send through in the opposite direction." Jim cautioned her.

"Can something actually squish you in the astral plane?" Tara smirked, "It's an accepted fact in both worlds that nothing can really hurt you there. Mickey isn't the 

one trying to pass through in new and creative ways. Besides, he moves faster than time--that bus would have to be going even faster to catch him."

"Joey's been my brother for thirty years. You just met him yesterday and you're already starting to talk like him." Jim grinned like an evil puppet, "Maybe my faith in 

fate and Destiny isn't so silly after all."

"Your little girl is still here on this side of the veil. My Dad is on the other side. I can't afford to have faith until the gateway is established and I can get him 

back."

"If we don't reopen the gateway, my big brother's going to disappear. I'm not supposed to know what will actually happen to him, but I might be the only one who ever 

does." Dealing with their mother could become very awkward if they didn't succeed, "I still can't believe it's possible for us to fail. Magic isn't like what they show 

on TV where every spell gets screwed up and everybody panics until it wears off and shit goes back to normal. Magic wants normal. It has this sense of right versus 

wrong that it's always seeking to uphold, and that's why humans have such a hard time using it. Humans don't care about right and wrong, they care about need, greed 

and revenge. We personalize everything and blow it out of proportion. Magic sees the big picture."

"In the big picture of two or more universes, does it see us at all? What is one teeny tiny little puckwudgie boy, when you and I are smaller than electrons?" Tara 

held the tiny glowing kid in the palm of her hand. He glowed confidently, as if he knew a secret she might never understand.

"He knows the difference between right and wrong, the same way all little kids do. Life in our world teaches us a different set of rules and regulations, most of which 

we never learn to like because they're wrong. He never learned anything like that, so as far as magick sees, he is bigger than the both of us. He risked his life to 

fly through a magick mirror just to do what he felt was right--magic must be loving him right now...." Jim felt silly using the word magic so seriously. Even after 

three years of trying to teach his daughter the possibilities of 'bippety boppety boo' he still felt goofy talking in such simplistic terms. He preferred to think of 

it as forces and mutant powers, things that were more acceptable in this day and age. He'd outgrown the childlike faith it took to accept half the situations he'd been 

in since his baby had been born. The night he saw her floating above her crib and called his brother in a sheer panic was forever burned into his brain. Somehow, Joey 

had gotten from his apartment in Ashland to Jim's In-laws place on the reservation in seconds, and neither one of them had a vehicle at that time. Jim remembered his 

parents' stories of all the freaky shit that his brother had pulled before the age of three, and his mother's stories about her impossible pregnancy before that. Joe 

and Jim had grown up in a haunted holy terror that nobody outside their family could comprehend, So Jim and his wife Haley had elected to raise their special little 

girl in Odanah, where the Natives still enjoyed a spiritual belief system that would be more comfortable for their child. Certain events still had to be kept secret, 

even the open-minded Anishinaabe's wouldn't believe half their tales, but at least she could tell some of her stories and the vilage elders would be entirely 

supportive. They loved the fact that she went flying in her dreams and saw other worlds, and Odanah had long left behind the days when they would have judged her for 

having a Chimoke for a father--They all thought highly of Jim Kane.

A cop car passed a little too slowly on the road that intersected the hiking trail, just a few yards away. The ATV Jim was riding would give them more than enough 

reason to circle back around and stop them, so they took off in opposite directions, Tara hiding their little blue friend and Jim distracting any law officers from 

her. He was very experienced when it came to screwing with the cops, it was a phase he'd gone through in his teenage years that these small town Barneys would never 

let him outgrow, in spite of the fact that all the budget cuts had cut their rescources in half and practice made him really good at losing what few officers hadn't 

gotten laid off up here. The piggies had more important things to do, of course, but luckily human nature made them chase after him to settle some imaginary personal 

grudge rather than trying to prevent any actual crimes from happening. He wondered idly if it was his own human nature that made him laugh so hard when he turned down 

a cowpath that their squad car couldn't fit through--what kind of idiot thinks they can catch an ATV with a car? He parked the wheeler at a friends house and took 

alleyways over to his brother's apartment. He needed to pick up Joey's cat, who didn't tend to trust anyone outside their family and would hide from anybody else. 

They'd decided to make Marty's place their base of operations, since the collective consciousness of this world tended to fuck woth Joe's metahuman duties and Marty 

wasn't a blip on their radar yet. Lucky for him, his brother's baby kitty wasn't in a hiding mood tonight and sat there on the bed, blinking slowly at him when he let 

himself into his brother's tiny, filthy apartment. He would have been cleaning for hours trying to find the little furball if she decided to play hide-and-seek in this 

dump. He dug her carrier out from under the bed, and she obediently curled up inside. She didn't mind her little cage, and as long as he didn't try to take her 

anywhere by car, the trip wouldn't be too bad for her. He emptied out her food and water dishes, and grabbed her Meow Mix, stuffing it all into a duffel bag his 

brother used for laundry--it was sitting on top of a huge pile of dirty clothes, so it wasn't hard to find. He took more alleys over to Marty's place, and saw the cop 

still circling, looking for him. Apparently they hadn't thought to check out his brother's place. They rarely did anymore, in spite of the fact that Kane was a very 

rare surname up here and everybody knew Jim and Joe were brothers. They'd never given each other up to the cops, no matter what the situation was and had done their 

level best to convince the police that they hated each other, and were not on speaking terms. When he was finally within view of Marty's back door, it sprung open. 

Tara had been watching for him. The cat seemed only mildly interested in the tiny flying humanoid, when they let her out of her carrier. She watched him with intense 

fascination, but didn't make any moves to swat at him, like she would have done with virtually any other small mammal. Mickey even landed right in front of her, 

looking right into her eyes, and all she did was blink at him and purr--not her normal response to any animal, but it was her usual response to people she felt safe 

around. Jim wondered if she'd let the puckwudgie pet her--it would be so cool if she gave him a ride on her back! However setting up her food and water dishes was more 

important and he had to go back for her litterbox. Tara would be a better babysitter for both the kids, and yes, Jim considered the cat his niece, just like his 

brother consider Jim's dog a nephew, although the dog could do more tricks. Of course the fact that the kitty obeyed verbal commands at all, was a sign of 

intelligence. She didn't respond to key phrases, but if you told her to do something, she'd just do it--but only if she trusted you. Jim's big old dog, Killerpuppy, 

had started developing the same communicative abilities ever since Joe had started spending a lot of time around him and Jim chalked it up to some kind of psychic 

thing that his brother radiated without knowing it. Some sort of side-effect of being a cambion, all their childhood pets had seemed to understand him as well. Soon 

the Kitty was all settled in, she had had so many nicknames over the past eighteen years, she answered to virtually anything they called her, and Kid, Baby, and 

Cutestuff were the ones they most commonly used. She totally ignore Tara, no matter how the girl addressed her, so the girl had taken to calling her 'Little Brat' a 

nickname the kitten wasn't at all unfamiliar with. Her Daddy called her that a lot, he seemed to like it when she agrued with him, and Jim had seen enough of those 

little arguments to know she was willful and stubborn and always got her way in the end. If she wanted to go outside, her Daddy's arguments would never convince her 

otherwise, even if it was January, and he knew how much she hated snow and cold. He'd try to talk her out of it for hours, and she'd just keep talking back, never 

budging from the door until he opened it. Then she'd race out and right back in, with a shocked and surprised look on her face that nobody could help laughing at. 

Joe got home and informed them that he had narrowed down the location of the weak spot. There was a bit of a peninsula, where the old wastewater treatment plant had 

recently been ripped down, and along the edge of it stood a half eroded chunk of concrete that shaped itself into a perfect little altar. When he'd drawn the gateway 

sigils on it and set the mirror in the center, they'd been able to apport and asport a few small objects back and forth from one side to the other, but it was still 

going to be tricky. The entire area was fenced off after the demolition, and it was a contaminated sediment area, lined with yellow signs forbidding wading, swimming, 

boating, etc. It was highly illegal for them to set one foot into that area, and the cops could drive right past them on Monks Lane. It was the only place they could 

perform the ritual, but any and all magick he could summon up on the earthling side of the veil had to channeled into the rift. Using it to try and keep the cops away, 

wasn't an option. They were on the cusp of a full moon anyway, so they would have to wait a few days. Cambion powers were strongest during the new moon, so a full moon 

was kryptonite to him. They'd have to play it by ear, until he had enough juice to do the ritual and get it done before his geis ran out or the realm had time to 

react.
